01:06:49.246 --> 01:06:51.666 A:middle
as location, contacts, and Wi-Fi

01:06:51.666 --> 01:06:52.076 A:middle
networks.

01:06:52.936 --> 01:06:54.596 A:middle
Next, let's talk about

01:06:54.596 --> 01:06:55.596 A:middle
compression and formats.

01:06:56.246 --> 01:06:57.306 A:middle
We've, we're making really big

01:06:57.306 --> 01:06:59.006 A:middle
advances here this year.

01:07:00.196 --> 01:07:01.356 A:middle
Now, of course, JPEG is

01:07:01.356 --> 01:07:02.706 A:middle
ubiquitous and has served us

01:07:02.706 --> 01:07:04.466 A:middle
really well over the last 25

01:07:04.466 --> 01:07:05.956 A:middle
years, but today we know that a

01:07:05.956 --> 01:07:07.966 A:middle
number of technologies offer

01:07:07.966 --> 01:07:09.066 A:middle
better compression and

01:07:09.066 --> 01:07:09.786 A:middle
flexibility.

01:07:10.516 --> 01:07:12.786 A:middle
And similarly for H.264, which

01:07:12.786 --> 01:07:13.816 A:middle
is over a decade old.

01:07:14.486 --> 01:07:15.786 A:middle
Now, compression's important,

01:07:15.846 --> 01:07:17.456 A:middle
but we must consider other

01:07:17.456 --> 01:07:18.896 A:middle
requirements, so let's look at

01:07:18.896 --> 01:07:19.396 A:middle
some of these.

01:07:20.106 --> 01:07:21.806 A:middle
So for example, today the line

01:07:21.806 --> 01:07:23.706 A:middle
between photos and videos is

01:07:23.766 --> 01:07:24.696 A:middle
blurred, and a lot of what we

01:07:24.696 --> 01:07:26.186 A:middle
capture is actually a

01:07:26.186 --> 01:07:27.266 A:middle
combination of both of these

01:07:27.316 --> 01:07:28.086 A:middle
types of assets.

01:07:29.016 --> 01:07:30.846 A:middle
We also have new sensors that

01:07:30.846 --> 01:07:32.936 A:middle
capture much richer images and

01:07:32.936 --> 01:07:34.306 A:middle
display them, displays that

01:07:34.306 --> 01:07:35.016 A:middle
bring them to life.

01:07:35.566 --> 01:07:37.176 A:middle
And finally, whatever we choose

01:07:37.206 --> 01:07:38.226 A:middle
has to keep pace with

01:07:38.226 --> 01:07:40.106 A:middle
ever-increasing resolutions.

01:07:40.846 --> 01:07:41.916 A:middle
And so for the codec, we've

01:07:41.916 --> 01:07:44.216 A:middle
selected HEVC because it meets

01:07:44.456 --> 01:07:45.506 A:middle
all of these requirements.

01:07:45.926 --> 01:07:47.736 A:middle
It offers up the 2x compression

01:07:47.806 --> 01:07:49.396 A:middle
at equivalent image quality, and

01:07:49.396 --> 01:07:50.646 A:middle
when you add up the billions of

01:07:50.716 --> 01:07:52.096 A:middle
photos and videos, or trillions

01:07:52.096 --> 01:07:54.086 A:middle
I should say, that adds up to a

01:07:54.086 --> 01:07:56.046 A:middle
lot of saved space.

01:07:56.046 --> 01:07:57.396 A:middle
HEVC is also hardware

01:07:57.396 --> 01:07:59.026 A:middle
accelerated across many of our

01:07:59.026 --> 01:07:59.806 A:middle
devices.

01:07:59.806 --> 01:08:01.506 A:middle
And finally, it supports photos,

01:08:01.786 --> 01:08:04.326 A:middle
videos, 4K and beyond, and a

01:08:04.326 --> 01:08:05.846 A:middle
number of new technologies for

01:08:05.936 --> 01:08:07.136 A:middle
capture and display.

01:08:08.146 --> 01:08:10.576 A:middle
We've also selected a new image

01:08:10.576 --> 01:08:13.206 A:middle
container called HEIF, or, as I

01:08:13.206 --> 01:08:14.546 A:middle
like to call it, "heef."

01:08:14.546 --> 01:08:16.846 A:middle
You can repeat after me, "heef."

01:08:18.276 --> 01:08:19.846 A:middle
HEIF supports the concept of

01:08:19.846 --> 01:08:21.446 A:middle
compound assets, so in a single

01:08:21.526 --> 01:08:22.766 A:middle
file, you can have one or more

01:08:22.766 --> 01:08:24.056 A:middle
photos or one or more images.

01:08:24.056 --> 01:08:25.076 A:middle
You can have videos.

01:08:25.076 --> 01:08:27.586 A:middle
You can have auxiliary data such

01:08:27.586 --> 01:08:28.766 A:middle
as alpha and Depth.

01:08:28.766 --> 01:08:30.446 A:middle
It's also highly extensible.

01:08:30.666 --> 01:08:32.366 A:middle
It supports rich metadata,

01:08:32.366 --> 01:08:34.486 A:middle
animations and sequences, and

01:08:34.486 --> 01:08:35.906 A:middle
other media types, such as

01:08:35.906 --> 01:08:36.366 A:middle
audio.

01:08:36.366 --> 01:08:38.486 A:middle
And finally, HEIF is an ISO

01:08:38.586 --> 01:08:40.306 A:middle
standard, which is critical for

01:08:40.306 --> 01:08:41.326 A:middle
ecosystem adoption.

01:08:42.416 --> 01:08:44.506 A:middle
Now, our standard APIs provide

01:08:44.506 --> 01:08:46.916 A:middle
direct support for HEVC and

01:08:46.986 --> 01:08:47.446 A:middle
HEIF.

01:08:47.836 --> 01:08:49.446 A:middle
And generally, it's transparent.

01:08:49.526 --> 01:08:50.716 A:middle
No opt in is required.

01:08:51.236 --> 01:08:52.586 A:middle
But there may be cases where you

01:08:52.586 --> 01:08:54.316 A:middle
want to explicitly control the

01:08:54.316 --> 01:08:54.866 A:middle
format.

01:08:55.026 --> 01:08:56.706 A:middle
So for example, if you're trying

01:08:56.706 --> 01:08:58.426 A:middle
to play a high-resolution movie

01:08:58.686 --> 01:09:00.046 A:middle
on an older device that doesn't

01:09:00.046 --> 01:09:02.296 A:middle
have hardware acceleration, in

01:09:02.296 --> 01:09:03.886 A:middle
this case, we'd provide you an

01:09:03.886 --> 01:09:05.106 A:middle
API that you can use to

01:09:05.106 --> 01:09:06.866 A:middle
determine whether a given file

01:09:06.866 --> 01:09:08.426 A:middle
-- in this case, an HEVC movie

01:09:08.606 --> 01:09:09.386 A:middle
-- would play well on this

01:09:09.386 --> 01:09:09.846 A:middle
device.

01:09:09.846 --> 01:09:11.726 A:middle
And if it doesn't, we can

01:09:11.726 --> 01:09:13.316 A:middle
automatically fall back to one

01:09:13.316 --> 01:09:15.086 A:middle
of the older formats to maintain

01:09:15.086 --> 01:09:16.306 A:middle
a great user experience.

01:09:17.666 --> 01:09:19.546 A:middle
So now, within our ecosystem, we

01:09:19.546 --> 01:09:21.506 A:middle
automatically use HEVC and HEIF

01:09:21.756 --> 01:09:22.826 A:middle
as we share between all

01:09:22.826 --> 01:09:23.886 A:middle
compatible devices.

01:09:24.496 --> 01:09:26.266 A:middle
But where, when we're unsure

01:09:26.266 --> 01:09:28.186 A:middle
that the recipient can decode

01:09:28.186 --> 01:09:30.326 A:middle
these new formats, we'll err on

01:09:30.326 --> 01:09:31.936 A:middle
the side of compatibility and

01:09:31.936 --> 01:09:33.526 A:middle
automatically transcode the JPEG

01:09:33.556 --> 01:09:35.206 A:middle
and H.264.

01:09:35.206 --> 01:09:36.386 A:middle
An example of this would be

01:09:36.736 --> 01:09:38.496 A:middle
putting photos in an email

01:09:38.496 --> 01:09:39.056 A:middle
attachment.

01:09:39.616 --> 01:09:40.686 A:middle
I'd really encourage you as you

01:09:40.686 --> 01:09:41.946 A:middle
adopt these new formats to be

01:09:42.016 --> 01:09:43.896 A:middle
thoughtful about compatibility

01:09:43.896 --> 01:09:44.736 A:middle
as you build this into your

01:09:44.736 --> 01:09:44.956 A:middle
apps.

01:09:45.936 --> 01:09:47.276 A:middle
So that concludes compression,

01:09:47.276 --> 01:09:49.026 A:middle
and let me now talk about

01:09:49.026 --> 01:09:51.246 A:middle
another new topic, Depth.

01:09:52.196 --> 01:09:53.456 A:middle
Now, we've all see Portrait Mode

01:09:53.456 --> 01:09:54.956 A:middle
on the iPhone 7 Plus, which

01:09:55.006 --> 01:09:56.626 A:middle
generates the Depth effect using

01:09:56.936 --> 01:09:57.606 A:middle
the two cameras.

01:09:58.286 --> 01:09:59.846 A:middle
Here's how we do it.

01:10:00.456 --> 01:10:02.536 A:middle
We capture simultaneous images

01:10:02.956 --> 01:10:04.746 A:middle
from both cameras and we then

01:10:04.746 --> 01:10:06.796 A:middle
use stereoscopy to compute

01:10:06.796 --> 01:10:07.096 A:middle
Depth.

01:10:07.096 --> 01:10:08.226 A:middle
This is the same as human

01:10:08.226 --> 01:10:08.626 A:middle
vision.

01:10:09.226 --> 01:10:10.526 A:middle
We store this in what we call

01:10:10.526 --> 01:10:12.876 A:middle
the depth map.

01:10:13.156 --> 01:10:14.436 A:middle
So in Portrait Mode, we take the

01:10:14.436 --> 01:10:15.966 A:middle
photo, the depth map, and then

01:10:15.966 --> 01:10:17.806 A:middle
we use this to blur the objects

01:10:17.806 --> 01:10:18.696 A:middle
that are in the background.

01:10:19.526 --> 01:10:21.026 A:middle
But what's really cool is that

01:10:21.026 --> 01:10:22.966 A:middle
in iOS 11, we're now storing the

01:10:22.966 --> 01:10:24.526 A:middle
depth map as part of what we

01:10:24.526 --> 01:10:26.656 A:middle
capture, and we're giving you

01:10:26.656 --> 01:10:29.586 A:middle
and your app access to the photo

01:10:29.586 --> 01:10:30.386 A:middle
and the depth map.

01:10:30.386 --> 01:10:32.406 A:middle
So you can load it up and then

01:10:32.406 --> 01:10:34.466 A:middle
you can use this to do your own

01:10:34.726 --> 01:10:35.486 A:middle
creative effects.

01:10:35.486 --> 01:10:36.826 A:middle
And let me show you a couple of

01:10:36.826 --> 01:10:37.666 A:middle
examples of this.

01:10:37.976 --> 01:10:40.696 A:middle
So I might take this photo and I

01:10:40.696 --> 01:10:42.286 A:middle
might decide to turn the

01:10:42.286 --> 01:10:44.356 A:middle
background into monochrome,

01:10:44.896 --> 01:10:46.306 A:middle
really highlighting the subject.

01:10:46.306 --> 01:10:47.466 A:middle
I might apply a more artistic

01:10:47.466 --> 01:10:48.196 A:middle
effect.

01:10:48.456 --> 01:10:49.696 A:middle
Maybe I'll replace this with

01:10:49.696 --> 01:10:51.096 A:middle
this pumpkin patch with blur

01:10:51.096 --> 01:10:51.436 A:middle
effect.

01:10:53.376 --> 01:10:54.846 A:middle
And you can imagine even more

01:10:54.846 --> 01:10:55.486 A:middle
creative effects.

01:10:55.486 --> 01:10:56.246 A:middle
In fact, these are just

01:10:56.246 --> 01:10:56.876 A:middle
examples.

01:10:57.226 --> 01:10:58.796 A:middle
The possibilities here are

01:10:58.796 --> 01:10:59.206 A:middle
endless.

01:11:00.196 --> 01:11:02.506 A:middle
Now, this is Depth for still

01:11:02.506 --> 01:11:02.896 A:middle
images.

01:11:03.296 --> 01:11:05.246 A:middle
We're also giving you access to

01:11:05.246 --> 01:11:06.986 A:middle
a lower-fidelity, real-time

01:11:06.986 --> 01:11:08.756 A:middle
Depth stream using the Camera

01:11:08.756 --> 01:11:08.946 A:middle
APIs.

01:11:08.946 --> 01:11:10.926 A:middle
And this lets you build

01:11:10.926 --> 01:11:12.376 A:middle
Camera-based applications that

01:11:12.376 --> 01:11:14.206 A:middle
will use Depth in a novel way.

01:11:15.546 --> 01:11:17.016 A:middle
So Depth is really a simple

01:11:17.016 --> 01:11:18.346 A:middle
extension to both our still

01:11:18.346 --> 01:11:20.496 A:middle
image and Camera capture APIs,

01:11:20.496 --> 01:11:21.916 A:middle
and we look forward to

01:11:21.916 --> 01:11:23.236 A:middle
everything that you're going to

01:11:23.236 --> 01:11:24.316 A:middle
be building on top of these new

01:11:24.316 --> 01:11:24.516 A:middle
APIs.

01:11:24.516 --> 01:11:25.526 A:middle
Really, really exciting.

01:11:26.256 --> 01:11:27.126 A:middle
Next -- yeah.

01:11:27.586 --> 01:11:29.836 A:middle
There you go.

